\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Canteen Dilemma experiment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Canteen Dilemma is two-player co-ordination game modeled similarly to
 the Consecutive Numbers example.
 The game gives the Consecutive Numbers example a thematic context by creating
 a narrative of two colleagues arriving at work every morning.
 Instead of being assigned a number, they are assigned a time they arrive
 in the morning.
 There are eight possible arrival times ranging from 8:00 am to 9:10 am
 in ten minute intervals.
 Like the Consecutive Numbers example, participants know their own arrival
 time and that the other person always has an arrival time ten minutes before
 or after their own.
 The game then consists of a series of rounds where participants have to
 decide between going to the canteen and the office.
 They also have to give an estimate of how certain they are that the other
 player made the same choice as them, but I'll ignore that for now and come
 back to it later.
 The narrative of arriving at work is continued: if both players arrived
 before 9:00 am, they have time to go to the canteen, which also nets the
 highest payoff.
 Both players going to the office together results in a lower payoff.
 Going to different places, or going to the canteen at 9:00 am or later
 is the worst option however and results in a penalty.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To iterate, there are 8 possible arrival times, which results in 14 unique
 possible arrival-time pairs.
 The game puts players at a dilemma in the following way.
 Players prefer to meet in the canteen before 9:00 am, and there are plenty
 of chances for doing so, since 10 of the possible 14 possible arrival-time
 pairs allows this (call this the set
\emph on
 late
\emph default
: {(8:50, 9:00), (9:00, 8:50), (9:00, 9:10), (9:10, 9:00)}) punishes a canteen
 choice no matter what).
 Imagine a player want to go for meeting the other player in the canteen
 as much as possible, i.e.
 in all the 10 cases.
 One of the 10 cases consists of the arrival pair (8:50, 8:40).
 But when a player arrives at 8:50, they do not know if the other player
 arrived at 8:40 (meaning canteen would be the lowest payoff) or 9:00 (meaning
 canteen would be the lowest payoff).
 A player might attempt to avoid this dilemma by deciding to not go to the
 canteen when their arrival time is contained in the 
\emph on
late 
\emph default
set, i.e.
 choosing the office whenever they arrive at 8:50.
 But if they do this, they might assume the other player would do the same.
 This entails the dilemma is repeated at 8:40, since this means that the
 other player might have arrived at 8:50 and gone to the office.
 This line of reasoning is called backwards induction and applies to all
 possible arrival times, which entails the unintuitive conclusion that the
 only safe strategy is for both players to go to the office no matter what
 time it is.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is due to the lack of common knowledge about the arrival time of the
 players.
 However, it's highly unintuitive in relation to common sense reasoning
 to decide to go to the office when arriving at 8:00 am, after having been
 told that the highest payoff is going to the canteen together when you
 arrive before 9:00 am, and you know the following: you both arrived before
 9:00 am, the other player know you arrived before 9:00 am, the other player
 knows you know you both arrived before 9:00 am (and so on for two more
 iterations).
 See also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "studying strategies verbrugge 2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for empirical evidence that people are more likely to act in accordance
 with forward inductive reasoning rather than backward inductive reasoning.
 In general, reasoning by backwards induction ignores previous moves in
 a game, while forwards induction takes these into account.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used logarithmic scoring as a proper scoring rule, in relation to asking
 players how certain they were that the other player made the same choice
 as them.
 Research literature on eliciting belief also show that forecasts elicited
 from observers through proper scoring rules are significantly more accurate
 and calibrated then those elicited from observers using an improper scoring
 rule.
 Calibrated is defined as: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a set of probabilistic predictions are 
\emph on
calibrated
\emph default
 if 
\emph on
p
\emph default
 percent of all predictions reported at probability 
\emph on
p
\emph default
 are true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Seidenfeld"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 There is also evidence that forecasts elicited by the logarithmic scoring
 rule seem to have significantly less dispersion than quadratic scoring
 rules even though both are proper scoring rules 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "eliciting beliefs proper scoring"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Asking participants for a certainty estimate also has other benefits.
 It helps alleviate some of what Verbrugge calls 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the danger of formal systems that posit a fixed bound on social cognition:
 everyone can reason up to order 
\emph on
n 
\emph default
but not on order 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "verbrugge logic and social cognition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This is because it allows differentiation between two players both choosing
 e.g.
 canteen.
 There might be a distinction in terms of applied ToM between those who
 choose canteen and those who do not.
 But there might also be a distinction within the group that chooses e.g.
 canteen in terms of their estimated certainty.
 Now for the experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to gather more information about the reasoning of the participants,
 they were asked a few post-game questions.
 If a game ended because a player had lost all of their bonus, participants
 were asked whose fault it was that the game ended.
 Participants where asked three other questions when the game ended, regardless
 the reason.
 These questions pertained to (i) what strategy the player had, (ii) what
 time they deemed it safe to go to the canteen and (iii) if it was common
 knowledge that they had arrived before 9:00 am, given an arrival time of
 8:00 am, i.e.
 their intuition about the concept of common knowledge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Method and design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Experimental environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experimental setup was implemented in oTree 2.1.35 software 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "otree"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and conducted on Amazon Mechanical Turk (AMT) which is an online crowdsourcing
 platform.
 AMT works as an online labor market where workers can perform human intelligenc
e tasks (HITs) for monetary compensation.
 The platform has been used by social and economic researchers in lieu of
 typical lab experiments with local university students.
 Experiments on AMT have been shown to live up to the standards set by other
 data collection methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Berinsky"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "buhrmester 2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and to provide reliable, replicable and more diverse data than legacy methods
 using American college students 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "crump"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "consecutive numbers book"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "horton"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mason"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rand"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Participants and AMT Settings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experiment included 714 participants.
 All participants gave informed consent to participate before being included.
 AMT also allows the researchers to apply a few different settings.
 Only turkers from Canada or the United States were able to enter the hit.
 Further restraints were used in order to only include those with an approved
 HIT rate of 98% or above and at least 500 completed HITs.
 41 of the 714 did not play the full game due not making a required choice
 in time.
 The experiment was run in batches of 50 participants at a time within a
 timespan of a maximum of one hour.
 Participants had access to our emails during the experiment for questions
 and feedback.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Payoff structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Participants received a participation fee of $2.
 Besides this, the experiment utilizes a logarithmic scoring rule which
 means the payoff is calculated as the logarithm of the probability estimate
 for the actual outcome, where a 99% probability estimate of an event occurring
 would mean assiging 1% estimate to the event not occuring.
 Participants were also given an initial $10 bonus which is reduced during
 the game.
 Every round results in a penalty which is taken out of their bonus depending
 on the choices they make and how certain they are that their colleague
 has made the same choice.
 Payoffs range from $0.01 to $9.21.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

If both players go to the canteen, their penalty is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(player-certainty)$
\end_inset

.
 If they both go to the office it is doubled: 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(player-certainty)\cdot2$
\end_inset

.
 If they go to different places it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(1-player-certainty)\cdot2$
\end_inset

.
 Players who dropped out due to time limit received no bonus or participation
 fee, while the player matched to them received their participation fee.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Materials and set-up
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After a participant had provided informed consent, participants were directed
 to a waiting page until they were matched with another player.
 After the groups were formed, players were directed to an initial introduction
 page, detailing the rules of the game, quouted below (see Appendix A for
 screenshot).
 This page was shown for 90 seconds before automatically starting the first
 round (the initial intended time limit was 240 seconds, but it was not
 used due to an unintended problem).
 The instructions were also shown on every subsequent round which lasted
 61 seconds, where players were given an arrival time and had to decide
 to go to the canteen or the office.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
These instructions will also be shown on the following pages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent

\series bold
Instructions for the game:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
This game is about trying to do the same as your colleague.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
Every morning you arrive at work between 8:00 am and 9:10 am.
 You and your colleague will arrive by bus 10 minutes apart.
 Example: You arrive at 8:40 am.
 Your colleague may arrive at 8:30 am, or 8:50 am.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
Both of you like to meet in the canteen for a coffee.
 If you arrive before 9:00 am, you have time to go to the canteen, but you
 should only go if your colleague goes to the canteen as well.
 If you or your colleague arrive at 9:00 am or after, you should go straight
 to your offices.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
At the beginning of each round you will know only your own arrival time.
 You will have to decide whether to go to the canteen or to the office.
 As a general rule, you will maximize your payoff by honestly choosing the
 option you think your colleague will also choose.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent

\series bold
Payoff and penalties:
\series default

\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
You start the game with $10.00 and will have to pay various amounts of penalties
 in each round, depending on how well you both do.
 Your challenge is to have as much money left as possible when the game
 ends, after which the remaining amount is paid out to you as a bonus.
 The game ends after 10 rounds or when you or your colleague has no money
 left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent

\series bold
Both go to canteen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
If you guessed correctly that both of you went to the canteen before 9:00
 am, you pay a small penalty proportional to how uncertain you were, e.g.:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
-$0.69 if you were very uncertain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
-$0.29 if you were somewhat certain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
-$0.01 if you were very certain.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent

\series bold
Both go to office
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
If you guessed correctly that both of you went to your offices, no matter
 what time, your penalty is doubled and proportional to how uncertain you
 were, e.g.: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
-$1.39 if you were very uncertain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
-$0.58 if you were somewhat certain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
-$0.02 if you were very certain.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent

\series bold
One goes to the canteen, the other to the office
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation
\noindent
If you guessed incorrectly and one of you went to the canteen while the
 other went to the office - or if any of you went to the canteen at 9:00
 am or after, your penalty is doubled and proportional to how certain you
 were, e.g.:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
-$1.39 if you were very uncertain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
-$2.77 if you were somewhat certain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
-$9.21 if you were very certain.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\noindent
In summary, try to do your best doing the same as your colleague.
 As a general rule you will minimize your losses by giving an honest estimate
 of the chances of doing the same as your colleague 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After clicking next or the timer running out, participants were directed
 to a new page (see Appendix B) with the corresponding round number.
 They were assigned an arrival time from the set {8:00, 8:10, 8:20, 8:30,
 8:40, 8:50, 9:00, 9:10}.
 The page had a time limit at 61 seconds.
 The 'instructions' from the previous page was shown below as well.
 After stating their given arrival time, particiapnts where asked the following
 question, assuming they were assigned 8:50 am: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

It is Monday morning and you arrive at 8:50 am.
 Where will you go?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The possible answers being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Canteen
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and Office
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which had to be selected before a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

next
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 button could be clicked, prompting the participant to the next page.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
After making the canteen/office decision, the next page (see Appendix C)
 asked them: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

How certain are you that your colleague has made the same choice as you?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This was based on a 5 point Likert scale, with possbile answers being very
 uncertain, slightly certain, somewhat certain, quite certain and very certain.
 The possible answers were used for the logarithmic proper scoring by assigning
 the probabilities {0.5, 0.625, 0.75, 0.875, 0.99} to each answer, respectively,
 which was used for the logarithmic scoring rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When participants had made their choice between the canteen and office and
 had given a probabiltiy estimate, they were prompted to a page showing
 a table for running results (See Appendix D).
 What round number they had just played, what time they had arrived including
 their choice and certainty estimate.
 It also showed the arrival time of the other player in all previous rounds
 including their decision.
 The penalty for each round was also shown.
 They were explicitly told below the table if they had both chosen to go
 to the canteen or office together, if they had made different choices,
 or if it had been too late to go to the canteen (a player had arrived at
 9:00 am).
 It also stated the penalty for that round, their total losses and their
 remanining bonus.
 This running results page had a time limit at 30 seconds, which would automatic
ally prompt a new round when running out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

